		<title>ATR 121 â€“ casting actors, Australian blackface, Derrion Albert, privilege and oppression</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/addicted/~3/9yU6r4-m_jg/</link>
		<comments>http://www.addictedtorace.com/2009/10/12/atr-121-casting-actors-australian-blackface-derrion-albert-privilege-and-oppression/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 12 Oct 2009 16:18:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>team@newdemographic.com (Carmen Van Kerckhove)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.addictedtorace.com/?p=250</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Why does Hollywood continue to whitewash movies by casting white actors to play characters that were originally people of color? A popular Australian TV show is being criticized for featuring a blackface skit, but can we apply American attitudes toward race to other countries? Would Derrion Albert&#8217;s death be any less of a tragedy if [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Why does Hollywood continue to whitewash movies by casting white actors to play characters that were originally people of color? A popular Australian TV show is being criticized for featuring a blackface skit, but can we apply American attitudes toward race to other countries? Would Derrion Albert&#8217;s death be any less of a tragedy if he wasn&#8217;t an honors student? Why are people often reluctant to admit the ways in which they experience privilege in addition to oppression? Carmen Van Kerckhove, Tami Winfrey Harris, Thea Lim, and Latoya Peterson discuss.</p>
<p>Addicted to Race is broadcast live every Sunday afternoon at 12 pm Eastern. You can <a href="http://www.blogtalkradio.com/AddictedtoRace">listen live on our BlogTalkRadio page</a> and call in by dialing 347-996-3958.</p>
